04404nam a2200649Ia 9781501731648DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017316487 a10.7591/97815017316482doi  a(DE-B1597)515170  a(OCoLC)1100463066  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB3279.H49bK58 2005eb 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a1932231 aKleinberg, Ethan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGeneration Existential :bHeidegger's Philosophy in France, 1927–1961 /cEthan Kleinberg. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (308 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tOn the Way to France ... -- tIntroduction -- t1. Emmanuel Levinas: de l'etre... -- tThe First Reading -- t2. Alexandre Kojève and the Hegel Seminar at the École Pratique des Hautes Études -- t3. The Dissemination of Kojève's Heideggerian Interpretation of Hegel -- t4. Jean-Paul Sartre -- tThe Second Reading -- t5. Jean Beaufret, the First Heidegger Affair, and the "Letter on Humanism" -- tThe Third Reading -- t6. Maurice Blanchot: The Writing of Disaster -- t7. Emmanuel Levinas: ... à l'autre -- tConclusion -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen we think of Heidegger's influence in France, we tend to focus on such contemporary thinkers as Jacques Derrida, Michel Foucault, and Jean-François Lyotard. In Generation Existential, Ethan Kleinberg shifts the focus to the initial reception of Heidegger's philosophy in France by those who first encountered it. Kleinberg explains the appeal of Heidegger's philosophy to French thinkers, as well as the ways they incorporated and expanded on it in their own work through the interwar, Second World War, and early postwar periods. In so doing, Kleinberg offers new insights into intellectual figures whose influence on modern French philosophy has been enormous, including some whose thought remains under-explored outside France.Among Kleinberg's "generation existential" are Jean Beaufret, the only member of the group whom one could characterize as "a Heideggerian"; Maurice Blanchot; Alexandre Kojéve; Emmanuel Levinas; and Jean-Paul Sartre. In showing how each of these figures engaged with Heidegger, Kleinberg helps us to understand how the philosophy of this right-wing thinker had such a profound influence on intellectuals of the left. Furthermore, Kleinberg maintains that our view of Heidegger's influence on contemporary thought is contingent on our comprehension of the ways in which his philosophy was initially understood, translated, and incorporated into the French philosophical canon by this earlier generation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aExistentialism. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny20th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173164840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731648423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731648/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles